Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop fallback | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call that needs waking | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token |
| `while (true)` | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var waitHandles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns the index of the handle that was signaled.
            // Index 0 = _newEvent (new item); Index 1 = token (cancellation).
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(waitHandles);
            if (index == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string item;
            lock (_lock) { item = _queue.Dequeue(); }
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle, waking the thread
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation guarantees exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

1. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → removed.** `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` is passed to `WaitHandle.WaitAny`, so the thread wakes immediately when `_cts.Cancel()` is called. No interrupt needed.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → removed.** The loop checks `token.IsCancellationRequested` and `WaitAny` returns index 1 on cancellation, so the thread exits cooperatively. `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`).

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`.** The loop now has a cooperative exit condition.

4. **`WaitOne()` → `WaitAny(waitHandles)`.** This lets the blocked thread wake on *either* a new event or cancellation — the key technique for replacing `Thread.Interrupt` on blocking calls.

5. **Added `IDisposable`.** `CancellationTokenSource` and `ManualResetEvent` are both `IDisposable` — leaking them causes timer and callback leaks.

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Applies here? | Details |
|---------|--------------|---------|
| **`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | ✅ | The original `Stop()` would crash on .NET 8 if `Join` timed out |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9)** | ✅ | Even if it compiles on .NET 8 today, it won't on .NET 9+ |
| **`WaitOne()` can't be interrupted by a token** | ✅ | Must switch to `WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` as a second handle |
| **Pre-existing race condition** | ⚠️ | If multiple `Enqueue` calls fire before `RunLoop` processes, `Reset()` clears the signal and later items stall until the next `Enqueue`. Consider draining the queue in a `while` loop inside the lock, or switching to `BlockingCollection<T>` / `Channel<T>` |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | ✅ | Always wrap in `IDisposable` or `using` — leaks timers and registered callbacks |

## Optional Further Modernization

If you want to go fully modern, replace the entire `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` pattern with a `Channel<string>`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.Cancel();
        _runTask?.Wait(5000);
    }

    public void Dispose() { Stop(); _cts.Dispose(); }
}
```

This eliminates the `ManualResetEvent`, `lock`, `Queue`, and manual thread entirely — `Channel<T>` handles all synchronization and the race condition is gone. But this is an **optional modernization**, not required for the Thread.Abort migration.
